Reference-contexts: In this paper, we describe two new architectures that represent cost-effective solutions for multi-user compositing, yet retain enough exibility to realize the variety of applications described. 2.0 Problem Definition The class of compositing functions is very rich. The VideoStation <ref> [11] </ref>, for example, can handle antialiasing, transparency, and arbitrarily shaped objects. <p> The compositing computation itself is also distributed onto M*N processor. A frame buffer and a processor are paired up to form a module, one module per source per user. This scheme is architecturally equivalent to giving a Vid-eoStation <ref> [11] </ref> to each user, since the VideoStation follows precisely this paradigm. 1. Single-port memory is assumed. Current multi-port memories are too small to implement video frame buffers, and are not in themselves an extensible solution for multiple users.
